CUMULATIVE RETURN

While daily returns are useful, it doesn't give the investor a immediate insight into the gains he had made till date. Especially if the stock is very volatile. Cumulative return is computed relative to the day investment is made. If cumulative return is above one, you are making profits else you are in loss.</b>

In [148]:
FORD['Cumulative Return'] = (1 + FORD['Daily_return']).cumprod()
VWAGY['Cumulative Return'] = (1 + VWAGY['Daily_return']).cumprod()

FORD['Cumulative Return'].plot(label='FORD',figsize=(16,8),title='Cumulative Return')
VWAGY['Cumulative Return'].plot(label='VW')
plt.legend()
Out[148]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x2702f6b09d0>

Showed the highest return for a $1 invested.

This plot show that FORD is way more attractive as the profit continues to grow after may 2020. Where the profit for VW plummet at the beginning of the year and slowly recovered to make small profits at the end of 2020 and beginning of 2021. </b>

car_list=['FORD','VWAGY']
closing_df=DataReader(car_list,'yahoo',start,end)['Adj Close']

tech_rets=closing_df.pct_change()

tech_rets

rets = tech_rets

area = np.pi*20

plt.scatter(rets.mean(),rets.std(),alpha = 0.5,s =area)

plt.ylim([0.01,0.055])
plt.xlim([-0.003,0.004])

plt.xlabel('Expected returns')
plt.ylabel('Risk')

for label, x, y in zip(rets.columns,rets.mean(),rets.std()):
    plt.annotate(
        label,
        xy = (x, y), xytext = (50, 50),
        textcoords = 'offset points', ha = 'right', va = 'bottom',arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->",
                            connectionstyle="arc3"))

We can see higher risk for FORD, however also higher Expected returns. Subsequently- Lower risk and lower Expected returns for VW

FORD - The 0.05 empirical quantile of daily returns is at -0.051. That means that with 95% confidence,

Our worst daily loss will not exceed 5.1%. If we have a 1 million dollar investment, our one-day 5% VaR is 0.051 * 1,000,000 = $51,000.</b>

MONTE CARLO ANALYSIS- analyze the impact of risks.

</b>

In [178]:
days = 365
dt = 1/days
mu = rets.mean()['FORD']
sigma = rets.std()['FORD']

def stock_monte_carlo(start_price,days,mu,sigma):
    price = np.zeros(days)
    price[0] = start_price
    shock = np.zeros(days)
    drift = np.zeros(days)

    for x in range(1,days):
        shock[x] = np.random.normal(loc=mu * dt, scale=sigma * np.sqrt(dt))
        drift[x] = mu * dt
        price[x] = price[x-1] + (price[x-1] * (drift[x] + shock[x]))
       
    return price

FORD.head()

start_price=1.00

for run in range(100):
    plt.plot(stock_monte_carlo(start_price,days,mu,sigma))
plt.xlabel("Days")
plt.ylabel("Price")  
plt.title('Monte Carlo Analysis for FORD')

In [180]:
q = np.percentile(simulations, 1)
   
plt.hist(simulations,bins=200)

plt.figtext(0.6, 0.8, s="Start price: $%.2f" %start_price)

plt.figtext(0.6, 0.7, "Mean final price: $%.2f" % simulations.mean())

plt.figtext(0.6, 0.6, "VaR(0.99): $%.2f" % (start_price - q,))

plt.figtext(0.15, 0.6, "q(0.99): $%.2f" % q)

plt.axvline(x=q, linewidth=4, color='r')

plt.title(u"Final price distribution for FORD Stock after %s days" % days, weight='bold');

We get a histogram of the end results for a much larger run. Now we'lll define q as the 1% empirical qunatile, this basically means that 99% of the values should fall between here
